@Database CFG_BBSCOLOURS

@Index HBBS:Docs/Misc/Index.guide/MAIN

@Node Main "HBBS:System/Data/BBSColours.CFG - Config File"

  Description:

  The BBSColours.CFG file is used to change the colours of menu options in
  all doors that use them.

  You can place a BBSColours.CFG file in HBBS:System/Data and/or in each
  node's directory and/or each conference's directory.

  E.g.

    HBBS:Nodes/Node1/BBSColours.CFG
    HBBS:Conferences/NewUsers/BBSColours.CFG

  Options:

    MenuTextANSI=<string>
    MenuOpenBracket=<string>
    MenuCloseBracket=<string>
    MenuHighlightANSI=<string>
    MenuDefaultOptANSI=<string>
    MenuPromptANSI=<string>
    MenuDefaultOptTextANSI=<string>

  All the options are just ANSI escape sequences and/or a couple of
  characters.

  If a door passed the following string to DOOR_MenuPrompt(), using
  the default option of 'P'.  This is what would happen to it.

  "Choose a fruit, [B]anana, [A]pple, [P]assion Fruit, [K]iwi :"

  "Choose a fruit, "would be in the colour that was active before
  the call to DOOR_MenuPrompt().

  All the '[' characters would be *replaced* by the string defined by
  MenuOpenBracket.  So you can have the brackets in different colours
  or you can use a different ascii character for the bracket, or you
  can choose not to have a bracket at all.

  The same goes for all the ']' characters and the MenuCloseBracket option.

  All the options between the '[' and ']' brackets are written to the
  screen after the MenuHighlightANSI is displayed, so you can use this option
  to change the colour of the text between the brackets.

  All text directly following a ']' is displayed after the MenuTextANSI
  is displayed, so you can change the colour of all of the menu options.

  The default item is displayed slightly differently.  Instead of the
  system using "MenuHighlightANSI" and "MenuTextANSI", the options
  "MenuDefaultOptANSI" and "MenuDefaultOptTextANSI" are used instead.
  These two options allow you to change the colour of the text that the
  default options are displayed in.

  If the string passed to DOOR_MenuPrompt() ends in a ':' then the ':' is
  replaced with MenuPromptANSI.  This allows you to change the style
  and colour of the prompt.  Note: always include an ansi escape sequence
  to turn the colour back to white after your new prompt is displayed.

  You can use an escape character in the configs, or you can use {E}
  instead, which will be translated into the escape character for you.

  E.g.

  MenuPromptANSI={E}[34m? {E}[37m

  Here's the most common ansi escape sequences:

  "<esc>[3Nm"  change text colour (N = number from 0-7)
  "<esc>[4Nm"  change background colour (N = number from 0-7)
  "<esc>[1m"   bold
  "<esc>[2m"   italic
  "<esc>[4m"   underline
  "<esc>[0m"    ansi reset (the console.device has a bug which returns the
               text colour to red instead of white, so use <esc>[0;37m
               instead)

  you can merge these together, e.g:

  "<esc>[0;3N;4N;1;4m"

  Colours are as follows:

  0 - Black
  1 - Red
  2 - Green
  3 - Yellow
  4 - Blue
  5 - Magenta
  6 - Cyan
  7 - White

  Remember that Amiga's display things as they are supposed to be, but PC's
  will use different (brighter) colours for bold text, underlined and
  italicised text may or may not be displayed.

  So if you have PC conferences, stay away from using italic or underlined
  text.

  The above applies to most machines using a PC graphics card in text mode.

  Machines using a pixel based GUI will probably display things correctly.

@EndNode

